It's super easy and super cheap.
Solid state analog-digital-converters have become such a commodity item that you can get USB radios based on a chip that was originally intended to be used in digital TV tuners for like $20. Antenna is literally just some scrap copper wire soldered to a $3 connector from amazon. Nailed to my ceiling with 3d printed plastic spacers.
Here's a link to get you started. The antenna you're gonna wanna use is the V-Dipole. There's no pic directly in the linked post, but there's links to a post on the antenna itself in the relevant subsection. All the necessary software is free.

https://www.rtl-sdr.com/rtl-sdr-tutorial-receiving-noaa-weather-satellite-images/

In short: 53.4cm elements, bent 120 degrees apart, open side facing south.
Understand fundamental laws, exploit them to see gorgeous vistas from space, elevate yourself, make your waifur proud.
